WEBVTT

1
00:00:30.479 --> 00:00:32.079
<i>The Grid.</i>

2
00:00:33.879 --> 00:00:35.719
<i>A digital frontier.</i>

3
00:00:37.639 --> 00:00:39.799
<i>I tried to picture
clusters of information</i>

4
00:00:39.879 --> 00:00:42.119
<i>as they moved
through the computer.</i>

5
00:00:43.319 --> 00:00:45.599
<i>What did they look like?</i>

6
00:00:45.639 --> 00:00:47.879
<i>Ships? Motorcycles?</i>

7
00:00:48.719 --> 00:00:51.199
<i>Were the circuits like freeways?</i>

8
00:00:51.279 --> 00:00:54.839
<i>I kept dreaming of a world
I thought I'd never see.</i>

9
00:00:56.279 --> 00:00:59.119
<i>And then, one day...</i>

10
00:00:59.199 --> 00:01:01.079
<i>You got in.</i>

11
00:01:01.119 --> 00:01:03.679
<i>That's right, man.
I got in.</i>

12
00:01:38.678 --> 00:01:42.238
And the world was more
beautiful than I ever dreamed

13
00:01:42.318 --> 00:01:44.998
and also more dangerous
than I ever imagined.

14
00:01:45.078 --> 00:01:46.838
Hop in bed, now, kiddo.

15
00:01:48.318 --> 00:01:50.158
Now, I met a brave warrior.

16
00:01:50.238 --> 00:01:51.278
Tron.

17
00:01:51.358 --> 00:01:53.798
<i>♪ Bom-ba-bom-bom bom! ♪</i>

18
00:01:54.078 --> 00:01:55.438
Tron!

19
00:01:55.758 --> 00:01:57.038
He fights
for the users.

20
00:01:57.198 --> 00:01:58.518
He sure does.

21
00:01:58.598 --> 00:02:02.798
Oh, man, he showed me things
that no one had ever imagined.

22
00:02:02.838 --> 00:02:06.398
There were these disk battles
fought in spectacular arenas.

23
00:02:06.478 --> 00:02:09.278
Cycles that raced
on ribbons of light.

24
00:02:09.358 --> 00:02:11.838
It was so radical.

25
00:02:11.878 --> 00:02:12.878
And together...

26
00:02:12.958 --> 00:02:14.038
You built
the Grid.

27
00:02:14.118 --> 00:02:17.878
We built a new grid
for programs and users.

28
00:02:18.358 --> 00:02:20.278
Now, I couldn't be
in there all the time,

29
00:02:20.358 --> 00:02:25.438
so I created a program in
my own image that could think.

30
00:02:25.558 --> 00:02:27.638
Like you, and me.

31
00:02:27.718 --> 00:02:31.557
And I called him Clu.

32
00:02:31.997 --> 00:02:34.237
Codified Likeness Utility.

33
00:02:34.357 --> 00:02:35.397
That's right.

34
00:02:36.157 --> 00:02:39.477
And Clu, Tron and I,
we built the system,

35
00:02:39.557 --> 00:02:42.517
where all information
was free and open.

36
00:02:43.397 --> 00:02:44.717
Beautiful.

37
00:02:47.077 --> 00:02:49.557
And then, one day,

38
00:02:50.597 --> 00:02:52.477
something happened.

39
00:02:55.197 --> 00:02:58.757
Something extraordinary.

40
00:03:01.397 --> 00:03:03.197
A miracle.

41
00:03:06.997 --> 00:03:08.317
What was it?

42
00:03:09.597 --> 00:03:12.437
That'll have to
wait till next time.

43
00:03:12.597 --> 00:03:14.517
I gotta get to work.

44
00:03:14.597 --> 00:03:16.077
I wanna go with you, Dad.

45
00:03:16.157 --> 00:03:20.917
Yeah, well, one day you will.

46
00:03:20.997 --> 00:03:22.517
I promise.

47
00:03:22.597 --> 00:03:23.997
To the Grid?

48
00:03:24.157 --> 00:03:25.597
Good night, Sam.

49
00:03:27.916 --> 00:03:31.956
Hey, what do you say tomorrow
you and I hit the arcade?

50
00:03:31.996 --> 00:03:34.716
You can have a crack at
the old man's high score.

51
00:03:34.796 --> 00:03:35.996
First game's on me.

52
00:03:38.636 --> 00:03:41.756
Can we play doubles?
On the same team?

53
00:03:44.316 --> 00:03:46.756
We're always on the same team.

54
00:04:08.236 --> 00:04:10.316
<i>Good evening.
Our lead story.</i>

55
00:04:10.396 --> 00:04:15.156
<i>ENCOM CEO and video game icon
Kevin Flynn has disappeared.</i>

56
00:04:15.236 --> 00:04:18.316
<i>He was best known for designing</i>
Tron <i>and</i> Space Paranoids,

57
00:04:18.356 --> 00:04:21.156
<i>the two bestselling
video games in history.</i>

58
00:04:21.236 --> 00:04:24.356
<i>Flynn took ownership
of ENCOM in 1982</i>

59
00:04:24.436 --> 00:04:27.835
<i>as the company skyrocketed to
the top of the tech industry.</i>

60
00:04:27.915 --> 00:04:32.235
<i>But things changed in 1985 with
the untimely death of Flynn's wife,</i>

61
00:04:32.315 --> 00:04:34.835
<i>the mother of
his young son, Sam.</i>

62
00:04:34.915 --> 00:04:36.915
<i>Recently, ENCOM board members</i>

63
00:04:36.995 --> 00:04:38.235
<i>have been troubled by reports</i>

64
00:04:38.355 --> 00:04:41.355
<i>of Flynn's erratic,
even obsessive, behavior.</i>

65
00:04:41.395 --> 00:04:45.155
<i>With Flynn missing, the
company is now in chaos.</i>

66
00:04:45.195 --> 00:04:47.435
<i>This afternoon, ENCOM's board</i>

67
00:04:47.515 --> 00:04:50.675
<i>moved to seize control from
Flynn's partner, Alan Bradley,</i>

68
00:04:50.755 --> 00:04:53.755
<i>vowing to return the
company to profitability.</i>

69
00:04:54.155 --> 00:04:55.355
<i>Loyal to the end,</i>

70
00:04:55.395 --> 00:04:59.075
<i>Bradley maintains his belief
that Flynn is not missing</i>

71
00:04:59.155 --> 00:05:01.795
<i>and is instead
pursuing his dream of</i>

72
00:05:01.875 --> 00:05:05.315
<i>"a digital frontier to reshape
the human condition."</i>

73
00:05:06.995 --> 00:05:09.395
<i>In there
is a new world.</i>

74
00:05:09.515 --> 00:05:11.715
<i>In there is our future.</i>

75
00:05:12.075 --> 00:05:16.035
<i>In there is our destiny.</i>

76
00:05:21.875 --> 00:05:23.795
<i>Even Flynn's
most ardent supporters</i>

77
00:05:23.875 --> 00:05:26.274
<i>are now acknowledging
a difficult truth.</i>

78
00:05:26.354 --> 00:05:29.154
<i>Kevin Flynn may have
simply run away.</i>

79
00:05:29.514 --> 00:05:32.234
<i>And while Flynn's loyalists
hope for his imminent return,</i>

80
00:05:32.314 --> 00:05:34.714
<i>there is perhaps no one
who wishes it to happen more</i>

81
00:05:34.754 --> 00:05:36.194
<i>than young Sam Flynn,</i>

82
00:05:36.234 --> 00:05:38.234
<i>now in the care of
his grandparents,</i>

83
00:05:38.394 --> 00:05:40.394
<i>and heir to an empire
in turmoil.</i>

84
00:05:41.314 --> 00:05:44.074
He's coming.
He promised.

85
00:05:44.114 --> 00:05:45.114
Sam, you have to eat.

86
00:05:45.194 --> 00:05:46.194
Let go of me!

87
00:05:46.234 --> 00:05:47.514
Sam?

88
00:05:47.594 --> 00:05:50.874
<i>What will become of Flynn's
legacy and the future of ENCOM</i>

89
00:05:50.914 --> 00:05:52.114
<i>will most likely depend</i>

90
00:05:52.194 --> 00:05:55.594
<i>on what becomes of this
now orphaned little boy.</i>

91
00:05:57.674 --> 00:05:59.754
<i>Sam! Come back!</i>

92
00:06:08.954 --> 00:06:11.114
<i>All cycle
units, stand by.</i>

93
00:06:51.793 --> 00:06:53.593
<i>All units, stand by.</i>

94
00:07:54.472 --> 00:07:56.192
Now that is a big door.

95
00:07:56.272 --> 00:07:57.592
<i>Welcome, everybody.</i>

96
00:07:57.952 --> 00:08:01.192
Please settle. I know it's
late, so I'll skip the pleasantries

97
00:08:01.272 --> 00:08:05.032
and hand things over to our
chairman, Richard Mackey.

98
00:08:07.152 --> 00:08:09.952
Thank you. Thank you.
Thank you, Claire.

99
00:08:11.872 --> 00:08:13.592
Tonight I am pleased to announce

100
00:08:13.672 --> 00:08:19.672
that ENCOM's last fiscal year
was our most profitable ever.

101
00:08:20.552 --> 00:08:21.591
Yes.

102
00:08:40.271 --> 00:08:43.791
At midnight the 12th version
of our flagship operating system

103
00:08:43.871 --> 00:08:46.231
will hit the shelves
around the world.

104
00:08:47.631 --> 00:08:50.071
<i>I'm sure it comes as no
surprise whom we have to thank.</i>

105
00:08:50.271 --> 00:08:52.271
The head of our
software design team,

106
00:08:52.351 --> 00:08:57.351
a man whose father's own
notable history with ENCOM

107
00:08:57.431 --> 00:09:00.191
helped make this company
what it is today.

108
00:09:02.711 --> 00:09:05.191
Edward Dillinger.
Well done.

109
00:09:05.591 --> 00:09:07.111
Well done.

110
00:09:11.071 --> 00:09:15.071
And this year, simultaneous to
the release of ENCOM OS-12,

111
00:09:15.791 --> 00:09:21.110
we will be making our debut
on Tokyo's Nikkei Index.

112
00:09:21.230 --> 00:09:26.110
ENCOM's stock will now
trade around the world 24/7.

113
00:09:27.550 --> 00:09:28.790
Huh? Oh, yes.

114
00:09:52.590 --> 00:09:53.910
Excuse me.

115
00:09:54.030 --> 00:09:55.350
Yes, Alan?

116
00:09:55.430 --> 00:09:56.990
Given the prices

117
00:09:57.030 --> 00:10:00.710
that we charge to
students and schools,

118
00:10:01.670 --> 00:10:04.390
what sort of improvements
have been made in Flynn...

119
00:10:04.870 --> 00:10:08.150
I mean, ENCOM OS-12?

120
00:10:11.270 --> 00:10:12.910
This year we put
a "12" on the box.

121
00:10:15.630 --> 00:10:19.029
OS-12 is the most secure
operating system ever released.

122
00:10:19.989 --> 00:10:23.829
The idea of sharing our
software or giving it away for free

123
00:10:24.349 --> 00:10:26.709
disappeared with Kevin Flynn.

124
00:10:40.389 --> 00:10:42.429
I know you're here.

125
00:10:42.989 --> 00:10:44.909
Let's make this easy.

126
00:10:47.789 --> 00:10:48.909
Come on, come on.

127
00:10:57.389 --> 00:10:58.669
Freeze!

128
00:10:59.389 --> 00:11:00.509
<i>Okay.</i>

129
00:11:00.829 --> 00:11:02.349
If there are no more questions,

130
00:11:02.869 --> 00:11:05.909
I would like you to meet
our next blockbuster.

131
00:11:06.029 --> 00:11:08.789
ENCOM OS-12.

132
00:11:10.629 --> 00:11:12.069
Whoa.

133
00:11:12.629 --> 00:11:14.469
Still a few bugs.

134
00:11:14.549 --> 00:11:16.229
What's that?
What is that?

135
00:11:20.428 --> 00:11:22.308
Just bear with us one sec.

136
00:11:22.388 --> 00:11:24.668
Make this go away now.

137
00:11:24.748 --> 00:11:27.708
Stop what you're doing.
Stop. Stop for one second.

138
00:11:27.748 --> 00:11:31.868
<i>...where ENCOM's chairman,
Richard Mackey, will be launching...</i>

139
00:11:31.908 --> 00:11:33.548
We go live
in 30 seconds.

140
00:11:33.668 --> 00:11:35.308
He's on the roof!

141
00:11:35.388 --> 00:11:36.804
Anyone know where
the master file is?

142
00:11:36.828 --> 00:11:38.228
I do.

143
00:11:39.668 --> 00:11:40.908
It's on the Web.

144
00:11:43.188 --> 00:11:44.868
We've got to stop this.

145
00:11:48.948 --> 00:11:51.228
I've got to ring
that opening bell.

146
00:11:51.628 --> 00:11:52.788
Make this stop now.

147
00:11:52.868 --> 00:11:53.948
It's locked.

148
00:11:53.988 --> 00:11:56.948
Just shut it down.
Shut it down! Now!

149
00:11:56.988 --> 00:12:00.028
Relax, Mackey. Relax.

150
00:12:00.268 --> 00:12:01.428
It's under control.

151
00:12:01.468 --> 00:12:03.588
Relax?
Our most valuable

152
00:12:03.628 --> 00:12:07.188
and most secure operating
system is out there for free!

153
00:12:07.268 --> 00:12:08.948
How am I supposed
to explain that?

154
00:12:09.028 --> 00:12:11.988
I don't know. Say it
was all part of the plan.

155
00:12:13.028 --> 00:12:15.148
A little gift from ENCOM.

156
00:12:15.268 --> 00:12:16.987
<i>Apparently,
ENCOM Technology</i>

157
00:12:17.067 --> 00:12:19.507
<i>is having some
technical difficulties.</i>

158
00:12:20.627 --> 00:12:23.867
<i>Why don't we give them a
chance to sort things out?</i>

159
00:12:50.947 --> 00:12:52.947
Hey, Dad.

160
00:12:53.027 --> 00:12:54.827
How you doing?

161
00:13:00.827 --> 00:13:02.627
Where you
gonna run to now?

162
00:13:02.747 --> 00:13:04.507
Hey, you don't wanna do that.

163
00:13:04.587 --> 00:13:06.907
Didn't anyone
tell you? Stealing is wrong.

164
00:13:07.027 --> 00:13:09.627
You can't steal what
was designed to be free.

165
00:13:09.667 --> 00:13:10.947
Now I got you.

166
00:13:11.347 --> 00:13:12.867
Your boss is okay with this.

167
00:13:12.947 --> 00:13:14.227
The hell he is.

168
00:13:14.667 --> 00:13:16.466
Your boss works for the CEO

169
00:13:16.506 --> 00:13:18.186
and the CEO works
for the shareholders.

170
00:13:18.226 --> 00:13:20.546
Do you know who the
biggest shareholder is?

171
00:13:21.506 --> 00:13:23.186
I don't know.
Some kid.

172
00:13:27.346 --> 00:13:29.106
You're Mr. Flynn?

173
00:13:30.946 --> 00:13:32.506
Why?

174
00:13:33.066 --> 00:13:35.506
This is your father's company.

175
00:13:35.546 --> 00:13:37.226
Not anymore.

176
00:13:37.386 --> 00:13:39.106
What? Hey. Hey, kid.

177
00:13:39.186 --> 00:13:41.866
No!

178
00:13:53.746 --> 00:13:55.026
Yeah.

179
00:13:55.426 --> 00:13:57.826
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa!

180
00:14:02.306 --> 00:14:03.546
You kidding me?

181
00:14:04.506 --> 00:14:06.306
That's him! Get
the team down here!

182
00:14:06.426 --> 00:14:08.226
There he is!
Get him!

183
00:14:09.906 --> 00:14:11.386
What the...

184
00:14:11.706 --> 00:14:13.865
Hey! No free ride!

185
00:14:14.505 --> 00:14:15.705
Whoa!

186
00:14:15.825 --> 00:14:17.025
No free taxi!

187
00:14:17.225 --> 00:14:19.025
You pay!

188
00:14:21.665 --> 00:14:22.865
Whoa, whoa, whoa!

189
00:14:22.985 --> 00:14:24.265
No free ride!

190
00:14:33.825 --> 00:14:36.865
Hold
it right there. Freeze!

191
00:14:38.745 --> 00:14:42.145
Okay, boys.
You got me.

192
00:14:42.945 --> 00:14:44.105
Hey.

193
00:14:58.905 --> 00:14:59.945
Hey, Karl.

194
00:14:59.985 --> 00:15:00.985
Hey, how you doing?

195
00:15:16.984 --> 00:15:19.344
Enjoy it, Marv.
You earned it.

196
00:15:23.384 --> 00:15:25.224
Why are you
in my apartment, Alan?

197
00:15:27.104 --> 00:15:29.184
You don't answer your phone.

198
00:15:31.664 --> 00:15:33.664
How you been, Sam?
Oh, you know,

199
00:15:33.704 --> 00:15:37.424
when I was 12, I appreciated the
surrogate-father thing. But come on.

200
00:15:38.144 --> 00:15:40.024
I got it all under control now.

201
00:15:40.464 --> 00:15:42.544
Oh. Clearly!

202
00:15:42.624 --> 00:15:44.040
You want to help me
with my homework?

203
00:15:44.064 --> 00:15:45.464
Like old times?
Have a catch?

204
00:15:47.824 --> 00:15:51.344
You know, you got a
pretty nice view here.

205
00:15:53.824 --> 00:15:57.304
Heard you did a triple Axel
off of her a few hours ago.

206
00:15:58.344 --> 00:15:59.664
Rough landing, huh?

207
00:15:59.784 --> 00:16:01.184
Could have been worse.

208
00:16:01.224 --> 00:16:04.064
I also thought your
message to the board

209
00:16:04.144 --> 00:16:05.304
was very clever.

210
00:16:05.344 --> 00:16:07.864
Did you like that?
That was Marv's idea.

211
00:16:13.503 --> 00:16:16.303
Alan, are we really
going to do this again?

212
00:16:17.143 --> 00:16:20.263
Do I really look like I'm ready
to run a Fortune 500 company?

213
00:16:20.743 --> 00:16:22.023
No.

214
00:16:22.223 --> 00:16:26.383
And truthfully, the company is
pretty happy with where you are, too.

215
00:16:26.703 --> 00:16:27.743
I bet.

216
00:16:27.863 --> 00:16:31.023
That way they can keep
doing whatever they want.

217
00:16:32.703 --> 00:16:37.143
You know, I guess what I find
curious is the crazy charities,

218
00:16:37.383 --> 00:16:39.703
the annual prank on the company.

219
00:16:40.063 --> 00:16:42.663
You have an interesting way
of being disinterested, Sam.

220
00:16:42.703 --> 00:16:44.543
Why are you here, Alan?

221
00:16:47.903 --> 00:16:49.663
I was paged last night.

222
00:16:49.743 --> 00:16:51.983
Oh, man, still
rocking the pager?

223
00:16:52.143 --> 00:16:53.663
Good for you.

224
00:16:53.743 --> 00:16:58.143
Yeah, your dad once told me I
had to sleep with it, and I still do.

225
00:16:59.303 --> 00:17:01.663
Page came from your
dad's office at the arcade.

226
00:17:05.423 --> 00:17:06.543
So?

227
00:17:06.663 --> 00:17:07.783
So?

228
00:17:08.943 --> 00:17:11.582
That number's been
disconnected for 20 years.

229
00:17:12.982 --> 00:17:16.582
Sam, two nights before he
disappeared, he came to my house.

230
00:17:16.742 --> 00:17:19.342
"I've cracked it,"
he kept saying.

231
00:17:19.422 --> 00:17:23.222
He was talking about genetic
algorithms, quantum teleportation.

232
00:17:23.342 --> 00:17:27.582
He said he was about to change
everything. Science, medicine, religion.

233
00:17:28.902 --> 00:17:31.182
He wouldn't have left that, Sam.

234
00:17:34.222 --> 00:17:35.582
He wouldn't have left you.

235
00:17:35.782 --> 00:17:39.302
Oh, Alan. You're the only
one who still believes that.

236
00:17:39.622 --> 00:17:42.502
He's either dead or
chilling in Costa Rica.

237
00:17:44.262 --> 00:17:45.262
Probably both.

238
00:17:45.822 --> 00:17:47.342
Look, I'm sorry.

239
00:17:47.422 --> 00:17:49.942
I'm tired,
and I smell like jail.

240
00:17:50.622 --> 00:17:52.702
Let's just reconvene in
another couple of years, huh?

241
00:17:52.742 --> 00:17:54.822
What do you say?

242
00:17:58.942 --> 00:18:00.182
Here.

243
00:18:01.382 --> 00:18:03.782
These are the keys
to the arcade.

244
00:18:04.622 --> 00:18:09.621
I haven't gone over there yet. I
thought you should be the one.

245
00:18:09.741 --> 00:18:13.141
Alan, you're acting like I'm gonna
find him sitting there working.

246
00:18:13.261 --> 00:18:17.061
Just, "Hey, kiddo.
Lost track of time."

247
00:18:20.621 --> 00:18:22.701
Wouldn't that be something?

248
00:18:32.301 --> 00:18:33.501
What?

249
00:21:49.418 --> 00:21:51.138
You son of a gun.

250
00:22:31.977 --> 00:22:33.537
Flynn.

251
00:22:39.497 --> 00:22:40.737
